Article 41 of the Constitution guarantees labour rights. Nurses, clinical officers and now medical laboratory personnel are on strike. Courts have declared the strikes illegal and recommended negotiations.
The demand for provision of protective gear for frontline workers, appropriate promotions, reasonable risk allowance, and comprehensive medical cover should be addressed.
The health workers’ unions are advocating that all their members and those on contract be retained or employed on permanent and pensionable terms and their salaries enhanced.
However, Kenya’s ballooning wage bill is unsustainable. Already, the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund have raised the red flag. Further, there is an ethical dimension regarding health personnel withdrawing their services during a pandemic.
Therefore, an honest dialogue between the unions and both the county and national governments is necessary. Although the President has declared total war against corruption, Kenya has been consistently ranked in global graft indices as one of the most corrupt countries.
In jurisdictions where the fight against sleaze has been successful such as Botswana, the battle begins to be waged at the top.
Although Article 77 of the Constitution restricts full-time State officers from participating in any other gainful employment, in other nations, the officers are barred from doing business while in office.



