A government parastatal runs the businesses of those who enter public office until they leave office. Kenya could explore this route. Wealth declaration by public officers should be made public. Any wealth that is not declared should be forfeited to the State. 
EACC should be an independent institution established within the Constitution. Periodic lifestyle audits of public officials should be mandatory. Public officials should disclose any companies and other economic entities that they have interest in.
All public procurement, except that of a security nature, should be made open so that all data on procurement is permanently available to all for scrutiny.
Although as a country we pride ourselves as a democracy that follows the rule of law, we have habitually fallen short of Article 10 on the values and principles of governance. The country’s leadership needs to recommit itself to the culture of rule of law.
Elephant in the room
The elephant in the room in the world, and more so in Africa, is how to productively and effectively engage the youth. They make up 70 per cent of the population in Kenya. It is the most educated, energetic, potentially innovative and creative segment. 
Unemployment and lack of entrepreneurial opportunities are the major drawbacks facing this group. Without economic democracy for this segment, current measures to deal with youth dis-empowerment will only be palliative.



