From the dawn of independence, ethnicised politics has been firmly entrenched on Kenyan soil through competition among the elites of the major five populous communities of Kikuyu, Kalenjin, Luo, Luhyia and Kamba.
A united inter-ethnic elite divides Kenya into tribes, then they symbolically unify them in pre-election, and sometimes post-election coalitions. Such elite is not interested in creating a nation out of Kenya’s micro-nations by championing the politics of ideology.
Even when the kingpin rallies his community into a coalition, it is the kingpins and a select few in the tribe who benefit. Even some elite of the other 41 ethnic groups are admitted into what Taban lo Liyong called ‘eating chiefs’.



