As we begin the year, on the cards are the BBI referendum, a series of by-elections and the 2022 elections. Political formations have started to crystalise. Uhuru Kenyatta’s Jubilee, Raila Odinga’s ODM and William Ruto’s United Democratic Alliance are the emerging main political outfits. Other small parties are waiting to embrace the handshake coalition.
Reform activists are trying through Kongamano La Mageuzi, Linda Katiba, Kenya Tuitakayo, other civic groups and their associated nascent political parties to find space in Kenya’s politics.
2021 will be the year in which we could witness erosion of the 2010 Constitution through the BBI constitutional amendments which, inter alia, seek to constitutionalise the hegemony of the major ethnic groups in the country through a pentagon shaped national executive.
Democratic constitutions are always negotiated. Currently, no law exists to guide the referendum process. However, to force BBI on the citizenry is to burn bridges, not to build bridges.2021 is a make or break year for Kenya, and we must handle it with utmost care.
